import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

try:
	purchase = pd.read_csv('online_shoppers_intention.csv')
except FileNotFoundError:
	print("The specified file was not found.")
except pd.errors.EmptyDataError:
	print("The file is empty.")
except pd.errors.ParserError:
	print("Error parsing the file.")



else:
    if 'Weekend' in purchase.columns and 'Revenue' in purchase.columns:
    # Confirm columns are binary (0/1) and cast them explicitly to integers if needed
     purchase['Weekend'] = purchase['Weekend'].astype(int)
     purchase['Revenue'] = purchase['Revenue'].astype(int)
    else:
     print("The required columns are not present in the CSV file.")

# Drop unnecessary columns
purchase.drop(columns=['OperatingSystems', 'Region', 'Browser', 'TrafficType'], inplace=True)

# Display the first few rows of the modified DataFrame
print(purchase.head())

purchase_filtered = purchase[(purchase['ProductRelated_Duration'] < 12000) & 
							 (purchase['Administrative_Duration'] < 1250) & 
							 (purchase['ProductRelated'] < 300) & 
							 (purchase['Administrative'] < 20) & 
							 (purchase['BounceRates'] < 0.10) & 
							 (purchase['ExitRates'] < 0.150)]


# Scatterplot after outlier removal
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x='ProductRelated_Duration', y='Administrative_Duration', data=purchase_filtered, hue='Revenue', alpha=0.5)
plt.title('Scatterplot of ProductRelated_Duration vs. Administrative Duration (Outliers Removed)')
plt.xlabel('Product_Duration')
plt.ylabel('Admin_Duration')
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x='ProductRelated', y='Administrative', data=purchase_filtered, hue='Revenue', alpha=0.5)
plt.title('Scatterplot of ProductRelated vs. Administrative (Outliers Removed)')
plt.xlabel('ProductRelated')
plt.ylabel('Administrative')
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x='BounceRates', y='ExitRates', data=purchase_filtered, hue = 'Revenue', alpha=0.5)
plt.title('Scatterplot of Bounce Rates vs. Exit Rates (Outliers Removed)')
plt.xlabel('Bounce Rates')
plt.ylabel('Exit Rates')
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, roc_auc_score, confusion_matrix
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
# Split into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y)

# Initialize and train Logistic Regression
logreg = LogisticRegression(random_state=42, max_iter=500)
logreg.fit(X_train, y_train)


# Predict on test data
y_pred = logreg.predict(X_test)
y_prob = logreg.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

X = purchase[['BounceRates', 'ExitRates', 'Administrative', 'Administrative_Duration', 
          'ProductRelated', 'ProductRelated_Duration', 'PageValues', 'Weekend', 'SpecialDay']]
y = purchase['Revenue']

# Extract feature coefficients
coefficients = logreg.coef_[0]
features = X.columns



# Plot feature importance
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.bar(features, coefficients)
plt.xlabel("Features")
plt.ylabel("Coefficient Value")
plt.title("Logistic Regression Feature Importance")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()
